Title: Desktop I — Residential Power Instability Mitigation & UPS Deployment + Progressive Hardware Failure, PSU Root Cause, and System Stabilization
Date: July–August 2017
Classification: Infrastructure Risk Mitigation / Electrical Stability & Hardware Incident / PSU Failure / System Rebuild
Status: Resolved
Priority: Critical
Affected Asset: Desktop I (Primary Desktop System), Home IT Infrastructure
Related Tickets: N/A

Executive Summary
Desktop I experienced progressive instability characterized by freezing, black screens, and intermittent boot failures. Multiple components were replaced through a structured, stepwise troubleshooting process.
After extensive hardware replacements and validation cycles, the root cause was identified as a failing Power Supply Unit (PSU), compounded by unstable residential mains voltage conditions.
Repeated unexplained system freezes, hardware degradation, and instability across multiple configurations were ultimately correlated with inconsistent external power delivery.
Following validation, a line-interactive UPS with Automatic Voltage Regulation (AVR) was deployed. Additionally, a dedicated voltage stabilizer and surge protection were implemented. Electrical sockets across the residence were upgraded with professional installation and verification.
This combined infrastructure remediation fully eliminated the instability. Long-term system stability was achieved and sustained for years thereafter.
Following PSU replacement and power infrastructure mitigation, the system operated in fully stable condition and was later reassigned (gifted) while fully functional. Since implementation, no recurrence of similar issues has been observed.

